snippet.textDisplay:
I saw that some english speakers and foreigners don't know something:




"Bravo" is used to be said when you are satisfied with something, liking it.. being proud.. Imma check the exact definition: Bravo: "used to express approval when a performer or other person has done something well." It comes from Italian and means brave only when you use it as an adjetive, then you can say that someone is "bravo, brava", not common in this century tho, it is most used as an expression in actual spanish, as you use "Olé", that means approval, triumph, or encouragement.

I decided to write this because some people were saying that you can say Bravo for men and Brava for Women in an expression context, also because I'm spanish with this I practise my English.
Give me your like :)
